In [25]:
df_new.drop(columns=['notes'], inplace=True)

Upon executing the function to see which columns have missing, or 'null,' values and the amount of missing values in each column, it is evident that one of the columns has more than the others. Given that there are 4287 rows int he dataset, and that the 'notes' column has 4287 missing/null values, I have dropped this entire column since there is no evident and apparent value of it to my analysis and visualization of this dataset. I could replace the column with unknowns, but since there are no non-null, or non-missing values, and it is a categorical column, the column does not carry much or any significance in this project.¶

In [39]:
df_new.loc[:, 'candidate'] = df_new['candidate'].fillna('Unknown')

When comparing the amount of missing values in the 'candidate' column to the amount of total valus in the datase, the result is that 287 of the 4287 values are null or missing. When executed, this converts to show that around 6.6% of the values in the 'candidate' column are missing and null from this dataset. Given that it is such important information to my analysis of this dataset, I do not feel comfortable dropping the rows with null values. Instead, since it is a column represented by categorical data, I will be replacing the null values with the term 'Unknown' to represent the fact that the candidate information, being their first and last name, is missing. This column shows the names of the winning candidate in each state for that election cycle. This is vital information. Later on as I continue to analyze this data, find correlations, formulate categorizations, and execute visualizations, I may be able to assign candidates based on winning party.¶

In [32]:
df_new = df_new.dropna(subset=['writein'])

Upon analysis, it was presented that there are only three missing values in the column for 'writein.' This means that out of 4287 entries of data int he entire column, only 3 are missing or null. When executed this converts to approximately %0.07. For my research, this is a highly insignificant number that I do not expect to impact further analysis. Additionally, I do not consider the data found int he 'writein' column to be especially necessary, so I feel comfortable simply removing the 3 rows in the 'writein' column that have missing values.¶

In [46]:
df_new.loc[:, 'party_detailed'] = df_new['party_detailed'].fillna('Non-Applicable')

Comprably to the 'candidate' column, I highly anticipate being able to map missing values in the 'party_detailed' to other columns. This column specifically, entitled 'party_detailed' represents fruther calrifications on the subsets of larger political parties for which candidates ran. These larger subsets are found in the column entitled 'party_simplified.' Upon first glance, I am able to see that there is a lot of overlap between the two columns. I would not be surprised to see that the majority of the values in each column are the same. I replaced missing values with 'Non-Applicable' as opposed to 'Unknown' because I believe that most candidates will be representative of tthe parties represented by 'party_simplified' and may not align with a lesser-known party. As such, 'Non-Applicable' is more accurate than 'Unknown.'¶

Here, I added a column that relied on and analyzed data from both the 'party_detailed' and 'party_simplified' columns. Both of these columns contain soley categorical data as they describe, whether in-depth or more simply, the party which the winning candidate was affiliated with at the time of their race and subsequent election. This is highly valuable data to the analysis and visualizations I want to engage in. Therefore, I mapped the values to numerical data, in which 'DEMOCRAT' was set to 0, 'REPUBLICAN' was set to 1, 'LIBERTARIAN' was set to 2, and 'OTHER' was set to 3. I chose these values to map by executing the function to show me to unique parties in the 'party_simplified' column. By doing this, I will be able to see correlations between parties and other numerical variables.¶

plt.title('Total Votes Cast in U.S. Presidential Elections (1976–2020)', fontsize=16)
plt.xlabel('Election Year', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Total Votes Cast', fontsize=12)
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(votes_by_year['year'])
plt.tight_layout()

plt.savefig('Total Votes Over Time.png', format='png')  

plt.show()

In answering the question 'How has the overall voter turnout changed over time?,' it seems that generally overtime, there is a greater voter turnout for eache election. I could associate this with the general increase in population that developed countries experience over time. There is a relativley steady decline from the 1980 and 1988 elections which may reflect attitudes toward national efficacy and political involvement. The 1992 election features a sharp increade in turnout, followed by comprable oscilations until the sharp uptick in 2008. I would attribute this to Barack Obama's election campaign, becoming the first Black person to win the race. He remained the most voted fro President until the unprecedented peak in 2020 between candidates Donald J. Trump and Joseph R. Biden. This was a highly contentious and publicized Presidential campaign, explaining the surge in votes cast.¶

This visualization displays the correlation between the different columns of numerical data through a heatmap. The numerical columns include the provided votes, both for each candidate and for the total Presidential election that year, as well as state identification information displayed as ‘state_ic’, ‘state_cen’, and ‘state_fips’. Given that the identification information was consistent for each state and was not a variable influenced by any other factors or values in the dataset, they had relatively low levels of correlation as seen on the visualization. Evidently, ‘state_ic’ and ‘state_cen’ share nearly identical data. The strongest correlation outside of that is between the amount of total and candidate votes. This makes sense given that the election is guided, in part, by the notion that the candidate with the most votes wins the election.¶

Party Performance Comparison¶

In [233]:
party_votes = df_clean.groupby('party_simplified')['totalvotes'].sum().sort_values(ascending=False).reset_index()

plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))
sns.lineplot(data=party_performance, x='year', y='candidatevotes', hue='party_simplified', marker='o')

plt.grid(True)
plt.tight_layout()

plt.savefig('Party Performance Over Time.png')

plt.show()

In answering the question 'How do the total votes received by each party compare?,' it is clear primarily the impact of the two-party system which dominates United States electoral politics, especialy regarding Presidential elections. At no point in any of the elections from 1976-2020 did third-party candidates, represented in this graph as either 'LIBERTARIAN' or 'OTHER' come within the range of total votes amassed by either the Democratic or Republican Parties. As I would have assumed having studied Political Science, the winning party osciliates generally every 8 years, which is representative of two election cycles and two Presidential terms (the maximum amount an individual can serve). This implies that voters align with an individual, followed by competing parties putting more resources into their own election. Interestingly, the graph shows that the popular vote was won by the Democratic Party for the last four cycles. Obviously, Republican candidate Trump won the 2016 election, but only through the electoral college.¶

Party Vote Percentage Share¶

In [229]:
party_votes = df_clean.groupby('party_simplified')['totalvotes'].sum()

plt.axis('equal')

plt.savefig('Votes By Party.png')

plt.show()

After completing this pie chart which used data from the 'party_simplified' column and the 'totalvotes' column, it is clear that third-parties including the Libertarian Party make up the vast majority of total votes cast in the Presidential election cycles from 1976-2020. Specifically, the Democratic and Republican Parties are nearly even at 13.3% and 13.3% respectivley. The Libertarian party specifically is closley behind at holding 11.6% of the total votes. Other parties, such as the Constitution Party, the Communist Party, or the American Independant Party, combined command just under 61.9% of total votes cast.¶
